			<title>News Hitman won’t be the last game Square Enix makes episodic</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?78406-Hitman-won’t-be-the-last-game-Square-Enix-makes-episodic&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Tue, 19 Jan 2016 22:38:50 GMT</pubDate>
			<description>Hitman won’t be the last game Square Enix makes episodic (http://arstechnica.com/gaming/2016/01/hitman-wont-be-the-last-game-square-enix-makes-episodic/) 
 
 
---Quote--- 
Earlier this week, the upcoming Hitman reboot was quietly removed from the PlayStation Store in Europe, with Square Enix...</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div><a href="http://arstechnica.com/gaming/2016/01/hitman-wont-be-the-last-game-square-enix-makes-episodic/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Hitman won’t be the last game Square Enix makes episodic</a><br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_description">Quote:</div>
	<div class="bbcode_quote printable">
		<hr />
		
			Earlier this week, the upcoming Hitman reboot was quietly removed from the PlayStation Store in Europe, with Square Enix cancelling pre-orders for the PlayStation 4 version. With the game scheduled for release in just a few months, fans were understandably concerned. Was the game being pushed back? Was it being cancelled entirely? The accompanying message, that the &quot;configuration of the product... has changed significantly,&quot; didn't help matters.<br />
<br />
It turns out that Hitman was pulled because the game will now be released episodically. <b>When it launches on March 11, Hitman will include a prologue mission and just one location, Paris, for the cost of £12/$15</b>. Its next location, Italy, will launch in April, with Morocco following in May. Each additional episode will cost £8/$10, or £37/$50 for a season pass. &quot;Regular monthly content updates&quot; that will include three additional locations—Thailand, the US, and Japan—will arrive later in the year.<br />
<br />
Or, players can pay for the whole lot upfront for £45/$60. The complete season will also launch on disc at the end of the year.<br />
<br />
While the public outcry over the move is understandable given just how close to release Square Enix made the switch, that the publisher has moved Hitman to an episodic format should come as little surprise. As a full-priced game, Hitman's release schedule was a convoluted mess. There was the full £50/$60 game, which which contained three locations—Paris, Sapienza, and Marrakesh—featuring six campaign missions. Players were promised access to a further three locations, as well as all online content without further charge.<br />
<br />
Then there was the £28/$35 &quot;Intro Pack,&quot; which sounded an awful lot like a more expensive version of what Hitman is now, giving players access to the launch content and nothing else. Players could then upgrade to the full priced release for £24/$30. Pity the soul that had to navigate that lot just to get their hands on the right version of the game.<br />
<br />
This terrifying array of price points and varying levels of access to content was a poor decision on Square Enix's part, or at the very least poor messaging. But the stigma once attached to &quot;episodic&quot; games—which I've no doubt was part of the reason the publisher avoided calling Hitman episodic in the first place—has been slowly disappearing, and Square Enix has become rather enamoured with it.<br />
<br />
Life is Strange, Dontnod's brilliant episodic adventure series, has been hugely successful for the publisher, while, despite the backlash, the upcoming Final Fantasy VII Remake will also be episodic. Delivering an adventure game episodically is nothing new of course—Telltale has been doing successfully it for years—while for a game like Final Fantasy VII Remake, going episodic was perhaps the only fiscally responsible way of translating its enormously detailed world into a modern engine.<br />
<br />
The question is, where does Hitman fit into that? It's neither a classic adventure game, nor does it appear ambitious enough to warrant a staggered release. Perhaps Hitman has simply been chosen as the guinea pig to see whether such a format will work for a big-budget shooter. Or maybe the game simply wasn't going to be finished in time, or at least up to the standards expected.<br />
<br />
Whatever the reason, don't expect Hitman to be the last franchise Square Enix moves to the episodic format. It's already done it with one of the biggest franchises of all time, and now it's doing it with another. Moving the others should be no trouble at all.<br />
<br />
This post originated on Ars Technica UK
			
		<hr />
	</div>
</div></div>

