			<title>So when something frustrates me, I put it into words</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?78400-So-when-something-frustrates-me-I-put-it-into-words&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Sun, 17 Jan 2016 09:24:04 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[I'm no professional writer, but I am married to one, heh. 
 
People used to tell me I should be a stand-up comedian, but that's a pretty shit job, so I dodged it. 
 
This just happened, about 2 hours ago. 
 
 
---Quote--- 
 
So we had several pounds of pork riblets to use.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>I'm no professional writer, but I am married to one, heh.<br />
<br />
People used to tell me I should be a stand-up comedian, but that's a pretty shit job, so I dodged it.<br />
<br />
This just happened, about 2 hours ago.<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_description">Quote:</div>
	<div class="bbcode_quote printable">
		<hr />
		
			<br />
So we had several pounds of pork riblets to use.<br />
<br />
They were SUPER cheap (&lt;$2/lb) and being the solutions-oriented person that I am, I concocted a way to cook them with what I thought would be minimal effort.<br />
<br />
6 quart crock pot, turn them into pulled pork for Cuban sandwiches.<br />
<br />
It’ll fall off the bones so I can pick them out with relative ease, the fat will melt off so there will be no trimming required, and they can go in completely frozen, so I don’t have to worry about uneven heating or thawing.<br />
<br />
Sounds ideal, right?<br />
<br />
I thought so too.<br />
<br />
In fact, it *was* ideal.<br />
<br />
The pork riblets get to the point where they have fallen off of the bone.<br />
<br />
I go through, pick the bones out, and start juicing some citrus fruit so I can go back to slow cooking them.<br />
<br />
Juice an orange. No problem.<br />
<br />
Grapefruit? Equally easy.<br />
<br />
Lime? Almost effortless.<br />
<br />
And then I see a can of Dole Pineapple Juice sitting on the counter.<br />
<br />
The sound of a change machine or slot machine paying out in loud coinage plays through my head. I might have even said “JACKPOT!” out loud.<br />
<br />
I knew we had two cans of the stuff.<br />
<br />
So, like you do, I grabbed the can and started to shake. Pineapple juice settles, and for full flavor profile, only truly homogenous pineapple juice, complete with pulp, would do.<br />
<br />
It should be pointed out, at this particular moment in time, that we have a side-cutting can opener.<br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.amazon.com/Good-Cook-Classic-Safe-Opener/dp/B000AX13US" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.amazon.com/Good-Cook-Clas.../dp/B000AX13US</a><br />
<br />
Instead of cutting the top of the lid, it cuts around the rim on the outside side. This means that not only do you not have sharp edges, you can put the lid back on the can and it looks unopened.<br />
<br />
I would like to stress that very important point.<br />
<br />
LOOKS<br />
<br />
UNOPENED<br />
<br />
Cue vigorous shaking for what felt like about 60 seconds, but was probably, in reality, only half of one second because, out of NOWHERE time slows down.<br />
<br />
If I were Neo and this was the Matrix, I would have been dodging at this exact moment, because slightly less than FORTY SIX OUNCES of Dole Pineapple Juice geysered skyward like some kind of fruity-flavored fibery Mount Saint Helens, bent on devastating all clean surfaces with its sugary fallout.<br />
<br />
Then, another half second or so later, in the space of a blink, I couldn’t see.<br />
<br />
I think to myself: “Hey, that pineapple juice is about to go everywhere. Hey, I can’t see. Ruh-Roh Rhaggy.”.<br />
<br />
So I stop shaking the can (like you do), open my eyes and watch.<br />
<br />
I watch as nearly an entire can of upwardly mobile pineapple juice explodes outward in a manner very much akin to the pictures from Alamogordo in 1945.  The lid flips towards the floor like a casually discarded shuriken, or perhaps Michael Dudikoff’s career in Ninja movies, and most of the juice?<br />
<br />
The lion’s share of it?<br />
<br />
Hits me straight in the face.<br />
<br />
I stand there, unwilling to move for fear of making a greater mess as all the waterfalls of Oahu start cascading off of my hair.<br />
<br />
Being conscious of fluid dynamics, I tilt my head forward so that it runs off of the front, past my eyes, so I can at least appreciate the view while I smell like an island paradise.<br />
<br />
Several seconds later.<br />
<br />
Still cascading. At least it smells pleasant.<br />
<br />
Drip.<br />
<br />
Crap. I’m going to have to do laundry.<br />
<br />
Drip.<br />
<br />
Crap, I don’t know where my wife keeps the mop.<br />
<br />
Drip.<br />
<br />
Crap, I…no, wait, we replaced the kitchen light, it’s enclosed, so nothing should short out.<br />
<br />
Drip.<br />
<br />
I really hope that didn’t hit either of the cats.<br />
<br />
Drip.<br />
<br />
Drip.<br />
<br />
Okay, it’s been 15 seconds, we’re probably good now.<br />
<br />
So I look around and take stock.<br />
<br />
Let’s just say I’ll be taking a shower and scrubbing a lot of surfaces.<br />
<br />
I’m not sure if I should be happy that my grey hairs have now been dyed blonde-ish.<br />
<br />
What a waste of perfectly good pineapple juice.
			
		<hr />
	</div>
</div></div>

